The model puts department in — and the odds multiply
\[
\small
\begin{aligned}
\operatorname{logit}(\pi_i)
&= \alpha + \beta_{\text{male}}\,\text{male}_i
   + \beta_{\text{eng}}\,\text{engineering}_i \\
\frac{\pi_i}{1-\pi_i}
&= e^{\alpha}\,\bigl(e^{\beta_{\text{male}}}\bigr)^{\text{male}_i}
   \bigl(e^{\beta_{\text{eng}}}\bigr)^{\text{engineering}_i}
\end{aligned}
\]


































[SLIDE 3/7 · clicks 2 · ~80s] Here is the model that produced the adjusted odds ratio. We predict the log-odds of admission from sex and from department together, so the equation now carries the confounder inside it as its own term. Because both predictors sit in the same equation, each coefficient is read with the other one held fixed. Beta-male is the sex effect, holding department constant, and beta-engineering is the department effect, holding sex constant. Because this model has no sex-by-department interaction, e to beta-male is one common conditional sex odds ratio across the two departments. This is the same holding-constant frame you already use for ANCOVA, now living on the logit scale. [CLICK 1] Now let us rewrite the very same model on the odds scale. When we exponentiate a sum, it becomes a product, so the sum on the log-odds scale turns into a product of factors on the odds scale, as the equation above shows. [CLICK 2] This is the key picture. Each predictor contributes its own factor, e to the beta sub j, which is the amount by which that predictor multiplies the odds. As a result, every coefficient exponentiates to its own adjusted odds ratio. [NEXT]
